Currently, in order to define Python-facing objects, we follow the standard Python methodology for defining an extension type (see eg https://docs.python.org/3/extending/newtypes.html). The problem with this approach are:
* This is idiomatic CPython, but not idiomatic C++. The code is hard to write and read.
* All methods have to be wrapped in macro-based wrappers that capture any C++ exceptions and translate them into Python code.
* Retrieving arguments/keyword arguments in methods is inefficient (it involves comparison of strings and format parameter scanning).
* Doesn't integrate well with `PyObj` objects.

The new system should aim to correct all these deficiencies. The expected API for defining an extension type is:
```C++
class Frame : public BasePyType<Frame> {
  DataTable* dt;

public:
  void m__init__(Args) override;
  void m__dealloc__() override;
  PyObj m__repr__() override;
  
  PyObj my_method1(Args);
  void my_method2(Args);
 
  static const char* classname() { return "datatable.Frame"; }
  static const char* classdoc() { return nullptr; }
  static void init_methods();
  static void init_getsetters();
};
```

