Hi,

I do not know if this can be considered as a bug, but the sum of an empty vector results in a runtime error:
```
dytest was compiled with optimization - stepping may behave oddly; variables may not be available.
Process 2070 stopped
* thread #1, queue = 'com.apple.main-thread', stop reason = EXC_BAD_ACCESS (code=1, address=0x0)
    frame #0: 0x00000001000018f4 dytest`dynet::Expression dynet::detail::f<dynet::Sum, std::__1::vector<dynet::Expression, std::__1::allocator<dynet::Expression> > >(xs=size=1) at expr.h:111 [opt]
   108  namespace detail {
   109  template <typename F, typename T>
   110  Expression f(const T& xs) {
-> 111    ComputationGraph *pg = xs.begin()->pg;
   112    std::vector<VariableIndex> xis(xs.size());
   113    int i = 0;
   114    for (auto xi = xs.begin(); xi != xs.end(); ++xi) xis[i++] = xi->i;
Target 0: (dytest) stopped.
```

Here is the code:
```
  1 #include <vector>
  2
  3 #include "dynet/dynet.h"
  4 #include "dynet/expr.h"
  5
  6 int main(int argc, char* argv[])
  7 {
  8     dynet::initialize(argc, argv);
  9     dynet::ComputationGraph cg;
 10
 11     std::vector<dynet::Expression> v;
 12
 13     auto e = dynet::input(cg, 4);
 14     //v.push_back(e);
 15
 16     dynet::sum(v);
 17 }
```

This may happens when working with structured losses (e.g. hinge loss). It is convenient to have a function which adds to a vector each wrongly predicted parts and then returns the sum of them.
A workaround is to write down something like `return v.size() > 0 ? dynet::sum(v) : dynet::input(cg, 0)`.

See: https://github.com/GoogleCloudPlatform/gcloud-python/pull/1642#discussion_r57048424 and ff.

Likewise `subscriptions.testIamPermission`.

@jgeewax if you decide so, please assign the issue to me;  otherwise, just close it.

